Keywords
*********
implementation, optimization, runtime, virtual machines, program analysis, =
garbage collection,=20
resources, Object-Oriented languages, prototypes.

Overview
*********
Object-oriented languages and similar languages are pervasive and play a si=
gnificant role
in computer science and engineering life and sometime appear as ubiquitous =
and completely
mature. However, despite a large number of works, there is still a clear ne=
ed for
solutions for efficient implementation and compilation of these languages i=
n various
application domains ranging from embedded and real-time systems to desktop =
systems.

The ICOOOLPS workshop series thus aims to address this crucial issue of opt=
imization in OO
and OO-like languages, programs and systems. It intends to do so by bringin=
g together
researchers and practitioners working in the field of OO and OO-like langua=
ges
implementation and optimization. Its main goals are identifying fundamental=
 bases and key
current issues pertaining to the efficient implementation,compilation and o=
ptimization of
such languages, and outlining future challenges and research directions.

Topics
******
Topics of interest for ICOOOLPS include but are not limited to:

* implementation of fundamental OOL features:=20
  - inheritance (object layout, late binding, subtype test...)=20
  - genericity (parametric types)=20
  - memory models=20
* runtime systems:
  - compilers
  - linkers=20
  - virtual machines=20
  - garbage collectors=20
* optimizations:=20
  - static and dynamic analyses
  - adaptive virtual machines
* resource constraints:=20
  - real-time systems=20
  - embedded systems (space, low power)...=20
* relevant choices and tradeoffs:=20
  - constant time vs. non-constant time mechanisms
  - separate compilation vs. global compilation=20
  - dynamic loading vs. global linking=20
  - dynamic checking vs. proof-carrying code=20
  - annotations vs. no annotations



